name: Piva, piva
comments: Traditional song from Lombardy, presumably originating as a lullaby. It was later played and sung by piva (or zampogna) players as a sort of "advertisement" for the door-to-door sale of olive oil. Zampogna players performing their songs door-to-door during the Christmas period are a typical Italian tradition, and the song has become a Christmas standard. Several Christmas-themed Italian adaptations of the lyrics were written, but "Piva, piva" is still much better known with its original lyrics in Lombard dialect.

name: The Last Rose of Summer
comments: "The Last Rose of Summer" is a poem by the Irish poet Thomas Moore, which he wrote it in 1805. The poem is set to a traditional tune called "Aislean an Oigfear" or "The Young Man's Dream" which was transcribed by Edward Bunting in 1792. The poem and the tune together were published in December 1813 in volume 5 of Thomas Moore's "A Selection of Irish Melodies". The original piano accompaniment was written by John Andrew Stevenson, but several other arrangements followed in the 19th and 20th centuries.

name: Haka
comments: A ceremonial dance or challenge in Māori culture. It is a posture dance performed by a group, with vigorous movements and stamping of the feet with rhythmically shouted accompaniment. Although commonly associated with the traditional battle preparations of male warriors, haka have been performed by both men and women, and several varieties of the dance fulfil social functions within Māori culture. Haka are performed to welcome distinguished guests, or to acknowledge great achievements, occasions or funerals. New Zealand sports teams' practice of performing a haka before their international matches has made the haka more widely known around the world. This tradition began with the 1888–89 New Zealand Native football team tour and has been carried on by the New Zealand rugby union team ("All Blacks") since 1905.

name: The Ballad of Casey Jones
comments: Mostly called "Casey Jones", this is about locomotive driver Casey Jones, who is said to on April 30, 1900, have tried to prevent his speeding train from crashing into another one. Nearly succeeding, he saved all passengers and, being the only one killed, became a legend. T. Lawrence Seibert/Eddie Newton were first to copyright the song, but many others credited themselves for the authorship and, like with all traditionals, the lyrics have been varied throughout the years. Jones having jumped in for another driver on strike, Joe Hill in 1911 wrote a widely known parody and called it Casey Jones - The Union Scab There are also closely related songs like, f. ex., Freight Train Boogie or Ben Dewberry's Final Run . Some consider J.C. Holmes Blues a parody and Grateful Dead took the matter to another level in their own song Casey Jones . First lines of the traditional song: Come, all you rounders, if you want to hear The story told of a brave engineer; Casey Jones was the rounder’s name A high right-wheeler of mighty fame Of mighty fame, of mighty fame
